Actor Alesh Ola Sanni has raised alarm over the spread of fake drinks by club owners. The actor and film producer urged Nigerians to be wary of the drinks they splash their money on. He said this via his Instagram page. “Lounge and club owners don’t be unfortunate, stop selling fake drinks at ridiculous prices, ahh stop killing people with poison.“Guys please use your phone camera to always check the barcode of drinks now. You can verify by scanning with your phone. “Some people can’t just make heaven, ridiculous amount on fake drinks. Chai Naija my country na we dey do ourselves.”Reacting to his post, actress, Kitan Bukola, said she has been lucky to bypass fake drinks due to her knowledge of the market. She said: “wo no be by barcode again, maybe cus I sell drinks sha. I know the original most time when I see it, especially Henny and Martel. I’m always vigilant with it, that’s why I have just one supplier.” (Thenation)      Some Nollywood artistes on Thursday paid tribute to their late colleague, Rasheed Abu, who died of an unknown illness. The actor’s death was announced by his friend and colleague, Yomi Gold, on Thursday on his instagram handle (iamyomigold). Most of the artistes took to their instagram handles to mourn the… In "Entertainment" Having spent 19 years in the industry, sensational singer, Kcee admitted that he had also "faked" it in the past.   Singer, Kingsley Okonkwo, popularly known as Kcee, has said that fans usually put celebrities under pressure to lead fake lives. He told SATURDAY BEATS, “90 per cent of celebrities lead fake lives… In "Entertainment" Ilorin - A cleric, Pastor Adam Kolawole of the Church of Christ Assembly, Ilorin, on Monday called for the prosecution of anybody caught selling fake alcoholic drinks in the country. Kolawole, who made the call in an interview with the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in Ilorin, said it was… In "Top Stories"